<!-- Modal Solar -->
<div class="modal fade" id="Solar" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="register form" aria-hidden="true">
	<div class="modal-dialog" role="document">
		<div class="modal-content">
			<div class="modal-header bg-secondary text-white">
				<h5 class="modal-title" id="exampleModalLongTitle">Solar</h5>
				<button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close">
					<span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span>
				</button>
			</div>
			<div class="modal-body">
				<p class="text-dark">Because of the abundance of sunlight, it has been a leader in personal renewable energy sources. 
				For residential homes, photovoltaic (PV) systems using solar panels are used. The initial costs are currently high, 
				but as current technologies in the field advance, and with the aid of government subsidies, owning a personal PV 
				system will only become easier.</p>
				<img class="my-3 img-fluid" src="~/img/sun3.jpeg" alt="Sun"/>
				<h5 class="mb-4 text-dark">Cost Per Killowatt Hour: 18 cents</h5>
				<p class="text-dark">
					References/Additional Information:
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li><a href="http://www.renewable-energysources.com/">http://www.renewable-energysources.com/</a></li>
					<li><a href="https://www.eia.gov/outlooks/aeo/pdf/electricity_generation.pdf">https://www.eia.gov...electricity_generation.pdf</a></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div><!--/Modal Solar-->

<!-- Modal Wind -->
<div class="modal fade" id="Wind" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="register form" aria-hidden="true">
	<div class="modal-dialog" role="document">
		<div class="modal-content">
			<div class="modal-header bg-secondary text-white">
				<h5 class="modal-title" id="exampleModalLongTitle">Wind</h5>
				<button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close">
					<span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span>
				</button>
			</div>
			<div class="modal-body">
				<p class="text-dark">
					Mainly generated by large wind plants, these are composed of large wind turbines that 
					are used as a means to generate electricity, and are already widely used throughout the U.S. 
					Some progress has been made for residential purposes, but currently farmers and those with open-air 
					fields of land are able to harness their own energy individually. The main hurdle wind energy sees 
					is the ability to store the energy generated and distribute it to areas where needed. This would 
					help the U.S. in general in forming a more efficient and “smarter” grid.
				<img class="my-3 img-fluid" src="~/img/windtower.jpeg" alt="Windmill" />
				<h5 class="mb-4 text-dark">Cost Per Killowatt Hour: 3.45 cents</h5>
				<p class="text-dark">
					References/Additional Information:
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li><a href="http://www.renewable-energysources.com/">http://www.renewable-energysources.com/</a></li>
					<li><a href="https://www.eia.gov/outlooks/aeo/pdf/electricity_generation.pdf">https://www.eia.gov...electricity_generation.pdf</a></li>
					<li>Pierce, Alan. "Building a Smart National U.S. Power Grid." Tech Directions 68.9 (2009): 10-11. EBSCOhost.</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div><!--/Modal Wind-->

<!-- Modal Hydro -->
<div class="modal fade" id="Hydropower" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="register form" aria-hidden="true">
	<div class="modal-dialog" role="document">
		<div class="modal-content">
			<div class="modal-header bg-secondary text-white">
				<h5 class="modal-title" id="exampleModalLongTitle">Hydropower</h5>
				<button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close">
					<span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span>
				</button>
			</div>
			<div class="modal-body">
				<p class="text-dark">
					As the leading renewable resource used in the United States, Hydro Powered plants 
					essentially rely on the movement of water. This flowing water pushes against turbines 
					to generate electricity.  Besides rivers for this kind of source, harsening waves of 
					the coast are also being considered as a means to generate electricity. In this context, 
					hydro-powered plants would be able to add its energy to the used power grid. As technology 
					improves, coastal regions could benefit more, and if advanced enough, the storage and transfer 
					of energy from hydro plants could provide more residential homes with renewable energy.
				</p>
				<img class="my-3 img-fluid" src="~/img/dam1.jpeg" alt="Dam" />
				<h5 class="mb-4 text-dark">Cost Per Killowatt Hour: 8.75 cents</h5>
				<p class="text-dark">
					References/Additional Information:
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li><a href="http://www.renewable-energysources.com/">http://www.renewable-energysources.com/</a></li>
					<li><a href="https://www.eia.gov/outlooks/aeo/pdf/electricity_generation.pdf">https://www.eia.gov...electricity_generation.pdf</a></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div><!--/Modal Hydro-->

<!-- Modal Biomass -->
<div class="modal fade" id="Biomass" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="register form" aria-hidden="true">
	<div class="modal-dialog" role="document">
		<div class="modal-content">
			<div class="modal-header bg-secondary text-white">
				<h5 class="modal-title" id="exampleModalLongTitle">Biomass</h5>
				<button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close">
					<span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span>
				</button>
			</div>
			<div class="modal-body">
				<p class="text-dark">
					If correctly utilized, biopower, or the burning of biomaterial for fuel, 
					can itself be carbon neutral, and, since it can be regrown, is considered 
					a renewable source. Some practices however, would result in a negative carbon 
					output. This is caused mainly by inefficient regrowth practices in the agriculture 
					industry. With advancement in technology, generating fuel from food and farm waste 
					can help reduce the size of landfills and can increase a home and surrounding area’s sustainability.
				</p>
				<img class="my-3 img-fluid" src="~/img/wood.jpeg" alt="Firewood" />
				<h5 class="mb-4 text-dark">Cost Per Killowatt Hour: 9.8 cents</h5>
				<p class="text-dark">
